vision film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Hawk''\n| Susie Hawkins\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Table 12''\n| Mel\n| Episode: \"Preserves\"\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Brotherhood of Poland, New Hampshire]]''\n| Helen Shaw\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Three Moons Over Milford|Three Moons over Milford]]''\n| Laura Davis\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Daphne''\n| Ellen Doubleday\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[A Room with a View (2007 film)|A Room with a View]]\n| Mrs. Honeychurch\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Dr. Faith Sutton\n| Episode: \"Harm\"\n|-\n| 2007\u201308\n| ''[[Freezing (TV series)|Freezing]]''\n| Elizabeth\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]''\n| Dame Celia Westholme\n| Episode: \"Appointment with Death\"\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''10 Minute Tales''\n| The Ex-Wife\n| Episode: \"The Running of the Deer\"\n|-\n| 2010\u20132015\n| ''[[Downton Abbey]]''\n| [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Cora Crawley, Countess of Grantham|Cora, Countess of Grantham]]\n| 52 episodes<br>[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]] <small>(2013, 2015)</small><br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]]\n|-\n|2020\n|[[War of the Worlds (2019 TV series)]]\n|\n|\n|}\n{{commons category}}\n\n==References==\n*[[Theatre Record]] and its annual Indexes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1527}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGovern, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film, television, and theater actor, and musician}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Elizabeth McGovern\n| image      = Elizabeth McGovern 2012.jpg\n|caption=Elizabeth McGovern at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|7|18}}\n| birth_name  =Elizabeth Lee McGovern\n| birth_place =  [[Evanston, Illinois]], U.S.\n|education = [[Juilliard School]]\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| spouse     = {{marriage|[[Simon Curtis (filmmaker)|Simon Curtis]]|1992}}\n| children = 2\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Lee McGovern'''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/uknews/9145002/Barack-Obama-hosts-State-Dinner-for-David-Cameron-at-the-White-House.html?frame=2168264&page=-60|title=Barack Obama hosts State Dinner for David Cameron at the White House|agency=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|location=UK|archivedate= November 18, 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118095900/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/uknews/9145002/Barack-Obama-hosts-State-Dinner-for-David-Cameron-at-the-White-House.html?frame=2168264&page=-60|url-status=live}}</ref> (born July 18, 1961)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/18/Famous-birthdays-for-July-18-Vin-Diesel-Kristen-Bell/8771563155558/|title=Famous birthdays for July 18: Vin Diesel, Kristen Bell|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=July 18, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019|archivedate=July 19, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190719181941/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/18/Famous-birthdays-for-July-18-Vin-Diesel-Kristen-Bell/8771563155558/|url-status=live|quote=Actor Elizabeth McGovern in 1961 (age 58)}}</ref> is an American film, television, and theater actor, and musician. She received an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for her role as [[Evelyn Nesbit]] in the 1981 film ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]''. She is also known for her performance as [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Cora Crawley.2C Countess of Grantham|Cora Crawley, Countess of Grantham]] in the British drama series ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', for which she has been nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award]]. Her other films include ''[[Ordinary People]]'' (1980), ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'' (1984), ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (film)|The Handmaid's Tale]]'' (1990), ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]]'' (1997) and ''[[The Chaperone (2018 film)|The Chaperone]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nMcGovern was born in [[Evanston, Illinois]], the daughter of Katharine Wolcott (n\u00e9e Watts), a high school teacher, and William Montgomery McGovern, Jr., a university professor.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/06/22/archives/katharinewatts-is-future-bride-of-law-alumnus-engaged-to-william-m.html | work=The New York Times | title=Katharine Watts Is Future Bride Of Law Alumnus; Engaged to William M. McGovern Jr., Who Is Harvard Graduate | date=1958-06-22}}</ref> Her younger sister is novelist [[Cammie McGovern]]. Her paternal grandfather was adventurer [[William Montgomery McGovern]], her maternal great-grandfathers were U.S. diplomat [[Ethelbert Watts]] and Admiral [[Charles P. Snyder (admiral)|Charles P. Snyder]], and her maternal great-great-grandfather was Congressman [[Charles P. Snyder]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/569221112.html?dids=569221112:569221112&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+19%2C+1958&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Marriage+Announcement+1+--+No+Title&pqatl=google | work=Chicago Daily Tribune | title=Marriage Announcement 1 \u2013 No Title | date=1958-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/519604002.html?dids=519604002:519604002&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+18%2C+1958&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Burnhams+to+Celebrate+in+West&pqatl=google | work=Chicago Daily Tribune | first=Judith | last=Cass | title=Burnhams to Celebrate in West | date=1958-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QrIXAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Mrs.+Charles+P.+Snyder,+wife+of+Adm.+Charles+P.+Snyder,+is+visiting+her+son-in-law+%22 |title = Army and Navy Journal|year = 1938}}</ref> During her early years, the McGovern family moved to [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], where her father accepted a teaching position with the law school at [[UCLA]].\n\nAgent Joan Scott saw her performance in ''[[The Skin of Our Teeth]]'' by [[Thornton Wilder]], was impressed by her talent, and recommended she take acting lessons.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} McGovern studied at the [[American Conservatory Theater]] in [[San Francisco]], and studied toward a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in Drama at the [[Juilliard School]] in New York City as a member of [[List of Juilliard School people|Group 12]] from 1979 to 1981.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hoggard |first=Liz |title=Elizabeth McGovern is the real dame of Downtown |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23892648-elizabeth-mcgovern-is-the-real-dame-of-downtown.do |accessdate=15 November 2011 |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=1 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112054709/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23892648-elizabeth-mcgovern-is-the-real-dame-of-downtown.do |archivedate=12 January 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1980, while studying at Juilliard, McGovern was offered a part in what became her first film, ''[[Ordinary People]]'', in which she played the girlfriend of troubled teenager Conrad Jarrett ([[Timothy Hutton]]). The following year she completed her acting education at the American Conservatory Theatre and Juilliard, and began to appear in plays, first [[Off-Broadway]] and later in famous theaters.\n\nIn 1981 she earned an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for her role as [[Evelyn Nesbit]] in the film ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]''.<ref name=\"Heawood\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article3327941.ece|title=Elizabeth McGovern: from Hollywood to a South London pub|publisher=[[Times Online]]|last=Heawood|first=Sophie|date=2008-02-08|accessdate=2010-03-31}}</ref> She then appeared in ''[[Beginners (1982 film)|Beginners]]'' (1982).\n\nIn 1984, she starred in [[Sergio Leone]]'s gangster epic ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]'' as [[Robert De Niro]]'s romantic interest Deborah Gelly. She had leading roles in two other films that year, ''[[Racing with the Moon]]'', a coming-of-age story also starring [[Sean Penn]] and [[Nicolas Cage]], and the comedy ''[[Lovesick (1983 film)|Lovesick]]'', as a patient whose psychiatrist ([[Dudley Moore]]) falls in love with her, risking his practice.\n\nIn 1989, she played [[Mickey Rourke]]'s girlfriend in ''[[Johnny Handsome]]'', directed by [[Walter Hill (filmmaker)|Walter Hill]], and the same year she appeared as a rebellious [[lesbian]] in [[Volker Schl\u00f6ndorff]]'s film ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (film)|The Handmaid's Tale]]''.\n\nMcGovern co-starred with [[Kevin Bacon]] in a romantic comedy, ''[[She's Having a Baby]]'', directed by [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]], and starred in the thriller ''[[The Bedroom Window (1987 film)|The Bedroom Window]]'', directed by [[Curtis Hanson]]. She teamed with [[Michael Caine]] in 1990's ''[[A Shock to the System (1990 film)|A Shock to the System]]'', a comic mystery about a man who plots the murder of his wife.\n\nIn a 1994 comedy, ''[[The Favor (1994 film)|The Favor]]'', McGovern played a woman who cheats on her boyfriend (played by [[Brad Pitt]]) by becoming her married best friend's proxy in a tryst with a man the friend has fantasized about.\n\nMcGovern appeared in a number of films in the 21st century, including ''[[Woman in Gold (film)|Woman in Gold]]'', a drama starring [[Helen Mirren]].\n\n===Television===\nMcGovern has appeared in several television productions, mostly in the UK. In 1999 and 2000 McGovern played Marguerite St. Just in a [[BBC]] television series loosely based on the novel ''[[The Scarlet Pimpernel]]''.\n\nOn American TV, she appeared in a 2006 episode of ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' titled \"Harm,\" in which her character of Dr. Faith Sutton was a psychiatrist accused of complicity in [[detainee abuse]]. Her other television work includes ''Broken Glass'' ([[Arthur Miller]], 1996); ''[[Tales from the Crypt (TV series)|Tales from the Crypt]]''; ''[[The Changeling (play)|The Changeling]]''; ''Tales from Hollywood''; the [[HBO]] series ''Men and Women'';'' The Man in the Brooks Brothers Shirt''; ''[[Shelley Duvall's Faerie Tale Theatre]]'' (\"Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs\"); and ''[[If Not for You (TV series)|If Not for You]]'' (CBS 1995, own series).\n\nIn May 2007, she played Ellen Doubleday, [[Daphne du Maurier]]'s paramour, in ''Daphne'', a [[BBC2]] television drama by [[Amy Jenkins]] based on [[Margaret Forster]]'s biography of the author.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2007/05/14/nosplit/bvtv14last.xml | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Last night on television | date=2007-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, McGovern appeared as Dame Celia Westholme in \"Appointment with Death\", an episode of ''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]''. In the same year, she appeared in the three-part BBC comedy series ''[[Freezing (TV series)|Freezing]]'', written by James Wood and directed and co-produced by her husband Simon Curtis. First broadcast on [[BBC Four]], it was also shown on BBC2 in February 2008. McGovern played an American expatriate actress named Elizabeth, living in [[Chiswick]] with her publisher husband, played by [[Hugh Bonneville]], and co-starring [[Tom Hollander]] as her theatrical agent.\n\nFrom 2010 to 2015, she portrayed [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Cora Crawley.2C Countess of Grantham|Cora Crawley, Countess of Grantham]], wife of [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Robert Crawley.2C Earl of Grantham|Robert Crawley, 7th Earl of Grantham]] (played by [[Hugh Bonneville]]) in the British TV series ''[[Downton Abbey]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/downtonabbey|title=Downton Abbey|website=www.itv.com}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nMcGovern is also a singer-songwriter. In 2008 she began fronting the band Sadie and the Hotheads at The Castle pub venue in [[Portobello Road]], London. The band released an album of songs she developed with The Nelson Brothers, who are now part of the band. The album also includes Ron Knights on bass and Rowan Oliver, borrowed from [[Goldfrapp]], as drummer for the recording sessions.<ref name=\"Heawood\"/> [[Michelle Dockery]], who plays McGovern's eldest daughter in ''Downton Abbey'', has occasionally sung with the band.<ref>''The Times'', interview with Michelle Dockery, 6 November 2010</ref>\n\n===Theater===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=May 2012}}\nRoles in New York include:\n*Melissa Gardner in ''[[Love Letters (play)|Love Letters]]'' ([[A R Gurney]]) at the [[Edison Theatre]], October 1989\n*[[Ophelia]] in ''[[Hamlet]]'' with the [[Roundabout Theater Company]] at the Criterion Center Stage Right, April 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/03/theater/review-theater-a-high-keyed-hamlet-starring-stephen-lang.html|title=Review/Theater; A High-Keyed 'Hamlet' Starring Stephen Lang|first=Mel|last=Gussow|date=April 3, 1992|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*Mrs. Conway in ''[[Time and the Conways]]'' at the [[American Airlines Theatre]], October 2017\n\nIn her theatre programme CVs (below), McGovern lists her other theatre work in the U.S. as including:\n*''My Sister in This House'' (Wendy Kesselman)\n*''[[Painting Churches]]'' ([[Tina Howe]])\n*''The Hitch-Hiker''\n*''A Map of the World'' ([[David Hare (dramatist)|David Hare]])\n*''[[Aunt Dan and Lemon]]'' ([[Wallace Shawn]])\n*''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' at the [[New York Shakespeare Festival]], Winter 1987<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/13/theater/theater-midsummer-night.html|title=Theater: ''Midsummer Night''|first=Frank|last=Rich|date=January 13, 1988|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*''When I Was a Girl I Used to Scream and Shout'' ([[Sharman Macdonald]])\n*''Maids of Honour''\n*''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' ([[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]])\n*''[[As You Like It]]''\n\nSince moving to London, McGovern's stage work has included:\n*Jenny in ''[[The Misanthrope]]'' ([[Moli\u00e8re]] freely adapted by [[Martin Crimp]]) at the [[Young Vic]] Theatre, February 1996\n*Darlene in ''[[Hurlyburly]]'' ([[David Rabe]]) at the [[Old Vic]] Theatre, March 1997\n*Nan and Lina in ''[[Three Days of Rain]]'' ([[Richard Greenberg]]) at the [[Donmar Warehouse]], March and November 1999\n*Beth in ''[[Dinner With Friends]]'' ([[Donald Margulies]]) at the [[Hampstead Theatre]], June 2001\n*Hester Prynne in ''[[The Scarlet Letter]]'' ([[Nathaniel Hawthorne]] adapted by [[Phyllis Nagy]]) at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], August 2005\n*Jackie Kennedy in [[Aristo (play)|Aristo]] at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], September \u2013 October 2008<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/oct/03/theatre1 |title=Aristo: Minerva, Chichester |first=Lyn |last=Gardner |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2008-10-03 |accessdate=2018-01-07}}</ref>\n*Judith Brown in ''[[Complicit (play)|Complicit]]'' by [[Joe Sutton]] in [[The Old Vic]], January 2009\n*Miss A in ''[[The Shawl]]'' by [[David Mamet]] in the [[Arcola Theatre]], September 2009\n*Veronica in ''[[God of Carnage]]'' by [[Yasmina Reza]] at the [[Theatre Royal, Bath]], August \u2013 September 2018\n\nMcGovern was awarded the 2013 Will Award by the [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Jessica|title=Backstage: Rorschach and Synetic thrilled with Kickstarter campaigns|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/backstage-rorschach-and-synetic-thrilled-with-kickstarter-campaigns/2013/08/06/17f9a9d8-fec0-11e2-bd97-676ec24f1f3f_story_1.html|accessdate=7 August 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1992, she married British film director and producer [[Simon Curtis (filmmaker)|Simon Curtis]]; the couple have two daughters, Matilda and Grace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/hollywood-never-suited-me-elizabeth-mcgovern-on-fleeing-la-and-downton-abbeyrsquos-lady-cora-2161323.html|title='Hollywood never suited me': Elizabeth McGovern on fleeing LA and Downton Abbey's Lady Cora|last=Gilbert|first=Gerard|date=18 December 2010|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Downton's Elizabeth McGovern: 'Ladies, never say never. It isn't over yet...'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/downton-abbey/11093415/Downtons-Elizabeth-McGovern-Ladies-never-say-never.-It-isnt-over-yet....html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Ordinary People]]''\n| Jeannine Pratt\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''Last Year's Model''\n| Unknown\n| S