{"title_page": "Anichkov Palace", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Coord|59|55|58|N|30|20|23|E|display=title}}\n[[File:Spb 06-2012 Nevsky various 04.jpg|thumb|The [[cour d'honneur]]]]\n\nThe '''Anichkov Palace''', a former imperial [[palace]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], stands at the intersection of [[Nevsky Avenue]] and the [[Fontanka]] River.\n\n==History==\n=== 18th century ===\nThe palace, situated on the plot formerly owned by [[Antonio de Vieira]] (1682?-1745), takes its name from the nearby [[Anichkov Bridge]] across the Fontanka. Designed for the Empress [[Elizabeth of Russia]] ({{reign | 1741 | 1762}}) in a dazzling [[Baroque]] style, the palace came to be known as the most imposing private residence of the era of Elizabeth Petrovna. Some{{who?|date=November 2019}} suggest architects [[Bartolomeo Rastrelli]] and [[Mikhail Zemtsov]] were responsible for the design, though that is yet to be substantiated. The main frontage faces the river and was originally connected to it by a [[canal]].\n\nConstruction works continued for thirteen years; when they finally finished in 1754 the Empress Elizabeth presented the palace to her favourite (and likely spouse), Count [[Aleksey Razumovsky]]. After his death in 1771, the palace reverted to the crown, but [[Catherine II of Russia| Catherine the Great of Russia]] ({{reign | 1762 | 1796}}) donated it to her own favourite, [[Grigory Potyomkin |Prince Potemkin]], in 1776. The architect [[Ivan Starov]] was charged with extensive renovations of the palace in the newly-fashionable [[Neoclassical architecture| Neoclassical style]], which were effected in 1778 and 1779. Simultaneously an English garden architect, William Hould, laid out a regular park. [[File:Anichkov.jpg|thumb|The colonnade of Her Imperial Majesty's Cabinet (designed by [[Giacomo Quarenghi]])]]\n\nUpon Potemkin's demise (1791), the palace was restored to the crown and adapted to accommodate Her Imperial Majesty's Cabinet.\n\n===19th and 20th centuries===\n\nThe last major structural additions occurred in the reign (1801-1825) of Emperor [[Alexander I of Russia| Alexander I]], with [[Giacomo Quarenghi| Quarenghi]]'s construction of the Imperial Cabinet along Nevsky Avenue. The latter structure was formulated in a rigorous Neoclassical style and many{{quantify|date=November 2019}} people feel that it doesn't complement Rastrelli's original work. Three years later, Alexander I bestowed the palace on his sister, [[Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna of Russia]] \u2013 she later became the Grand Duchess of Mecklenburg-Schwerin by marriage. Several architects have worked on the edifice since then, and its interiors were continuously refurbished.\n\nFollowing his marriage in 1866 the future [[Tsar Alexander III]] and his wife, [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark) |Maria Feodorovna]], made the Anichkov Palace their St. Petersburg residence, ensuring its refacing in a variety of historic styles. There their children, including the last Russian emperor, [[Nicholas II of Russia| Nicholas II]], spent their childhood years, and after Alexander III came to the throne in 1881, he preferred to stay at the Anichkov Palace (as opposed to the [[Winter Palace]]). The Anichkov provided the setting for numerous family festivities, including the wedding of Emperor Nicholas's niece [[Princess Irina of Russia |Irina Romanova]] to Prince [[Felix Yusupov]] in 1914. Nicholas II's mother, after becoming dowager empress, continued to have the right of residence in the palace until the [[February Revolution]] of 1917, although she had moved to Kiev away from St. Petersburg. After the revolution the Ministry of Provisions moved in.\n\nFollowing the [[October Revolution]] of November 1917, the Bolshevik government nationalized the Anichkov Palace  and designated it the St. Petersburg City Museum. After 1934, when it was converted into the [[Young Pioneer Palace]], the palace housed over one-hundred after-school clubs for more than 10,000 children. While a small museum inside is open to the public at selected times, the edifice is normally not accessible to tourists.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Anichkov fontanka.jpg|Anichkov Bridge and Anichkov Palace in 1753.\nImage:Anichkov palace. 1750.jpg|Palace in the 1750s: Elizabethan Baroque at its most flamboyant\nImage:Fontanka anichkov 1838.jpg|Palace in the 1830s: after the Neoclassical renovation\nImage:Anichkov sadovnikov.jpg|Palace in 1862.\nImage:Anichkov interior.jpg|Interior of one of the halls in the early 20th century\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n* Axelrod V.I., Bulankova L.P. ''Anichkov dvorets \u2013 legendy i byli''. SPb, 1996.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Anichkov Palace}}\n* [http://www.anichkov.ru Official website]\n* [http://www.encspb.ru/en/article.php?kod=2804002956 Anichkov Palace in Encyclopaedia of St. Petersburg]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Imperial palaces in Russia}}\n{{Nevsky Prospekt between Sadovaya Street and Fontanka River}}\n\n[[Category:Palaces in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Royal residences in Russia]]\n[[Category:Nevsky Prospekt]]\n[[Category:Carlo Rossi buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:1754 establishments in the Russian Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Coord|59|55|58|N|30|20|23|E|display=title}}\n[[File:Spb 06-2012 Nevsky various 04.jpg|thumb|The [[cour d'honneur]]]]\n\nThe '''Anichkov Palace''', a former imperial [[palace]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], stands at the intersection of [[Nevsky Avenue]] and the [[Fontanka]] River.\n\n==History==\n=== 18th century ===\nThe palace, situated on the plot formerly owned by [[Antonio de Vieira]] (1682?-1745), takes its name from the nearby [[Anichkov Bridge]] across the Fontanka. Designed for the Empress [[Elizabeth of Russia]] ({{reign | 1741 | 1762}}) in a dazzling [[Baroque]] style, the palace came to be known as the most imposing private residence of the era of Elizabeth Petrovna. Some{{who?|date=November 2019}} suggest architects [[Bartolomeo Rastrelli]] and [[Mikhail Zemtsov]] were responsible for the design, though it's yet to be substantiated. The main frontage faces the river and was originally connected to it by a [[canal]].\n\nConstruction works continued for thirteen years; when they finally finished in 1754 the Empress Elizabeth presented the palace to her favourite (and likely spouse), Count [[Aleksey Razumovsky]]. After his death in 1771, the palace reverted to the crown, but [[Catherine II of Russia| Catherine the Great of Russia]] ({{reign | 1762 | 1796}}) donated it to her own favourite, [[Grigory Potyomkin |Prince Potemkin]], in 1776. The architect [[Ivan Starov]] was charged with extensive renovations of the palace in the newly-fashionable [[Neoclassical architecture| Neoclassical style]], which were effected in 1778 and 1779. Simultaneously an English garden architect, William Hould, laid out a regular park. [[File:Anichkov.jpg|thumb|The colonnade of Her Imperial Majesty's Cabinet (designed by [[Giacomo Quarenghi]])]]\n\nUpon Potemkin's demise (1791), the palace was restored to the crown and adapted to accommodate Her Imperial Majesty's Cabinet.\n\n===19th and 20th centuries===\n\nThe last major structural additions occurred in the reign (1801-1825) of Emperor [[Alexander I of Russia| Alexander I]], with [[Giacomo Quarenghi| Quarenghi]]'s construction of the Imperial Cabinet along Nevsky Avenue. The latter structure was formulated in a rigorous Neoclassical style and many{{quantify|date=November 2019}} people feel that it doesn't complement Rastrelli's original work. Three years later, Alexander I bestowed the palace on his sister, [[Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna of Russia]] \u2013 she later became the Grand Duchess of Mecklenburg-Schwerin by marriage. Several architects have worked on the edifice since then, and its interiors were continuously refurbished.\n\nFollowing his marriage in 1866 the future [[Tsar Alexander III]] and his wife, [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark) |Maria Feodorovna]], made the Anichkov Palace their St. Petersburg residence, ensuring its refacing in a variety of historic styles. There their children, including the last Russian emperor, [[Nicholas II of Russia| Nicholas II]], spent their childhood years, and after Alexander III came to the throne in 1881, he preferred to stay at the Anichkov Palace (as opposed to the [[Winter Palace]]). The Anichkov provided the setting for numerous family festivities, including the wedding of Emperor Nicholas's niece [[Princess Irina of Russia |Irina Romanova]] to Prince [[Felix Yusupov]] in 1914. Nicholas II's mother, after becoming dowager empress, continued to have the right of residence in the palace until the [[February Revolution]] of 1917, although she had moved to Kiev away from St. Petersburg. After the revolution the Ministry of Provisions moved in.\n\nFollowing the [[October Revolution]] of November 1917, the Bolshevik government nationalized the Anichkov Palace  and designated it the St. Petersburg City Museum. After 1934, when it was converted into the [[Young Pioneer Palace]], the palace housed over one-hundred after-school clubs for more than 10,000 children. While a small museum inside is open to the public at selected times, the edifice is normally not accessible to tourists.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Anichkov fontanka.jpg|Anichkov Bridge and Anichkov Palace in 1753.\nImage:Anichkov palace. 1750.jpg|Palace in the 1750s: Elizabethan Baroque at its most flamboyant\nImage:Fontanka anichkov 1838.jpg|Palace in the 1830s: after the Neoclassical renovation\nImage:Anichkov sadovnikov.jpg|Palace in 1862.\nImage:Anichkov interior.jpg|Interior of one of the halls in the early 20th century\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n* Axelrod V.I., Bulankova L.P. ''Anichkov dvorets \u2013 legendy i byli''. SPb, 1996.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Anichkov Palace}}\n* [http://www.anichkov.ru Official website]\n* [http://www.encspb.ru/en/article.php?kod=2804002956 Anichkov Palace in Encyclopaedia of St. Petersburg]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Imperial palaces in Russia}}\n{{Nevsky Prospekt between Sadovaya Street and Fontanka River}}\n\n[[Category:Palaces in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Royal residences in Russia]]\n[[Category:Nevsky Prospekt]]\n[[Category:Carlo Rossi buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:1754 establishments in the Russian Empire]]\n", "name_user": "JSlip", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e18th century", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anichkov_Palace"}
{"title_page": "Peter Pettigrew", "text_new": "{{About||the fictional character in the Harry Potter series of novels and films|Peter Pettigrew (character)|the Canadian politician|Pierre Pettigrew}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Peter Pettigrew\n| image = \n| fullname = Peter Pettigrew\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|09|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = East Reservoir\n| height = 177 cm\n| weight = 72.5 kg\n| position = \n| statsend = 1972\n| years1 = 1970\u201372\n| club1 = {{AFL Col}}\n| games_goals1 = 19 (5)\n| careerhighlights = \n}}\t\t\n\t\t\n'''Peter Pettigrew''' (born 9 September 1950) is  a former [[Australian rules football]]er who played with [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] (VFL). He is also known for betraying the parents of Harry Potter, leading to their demise at the hands of Lord Voldemort. He has the ability to transform himself into a rat, and is currently deceased after strangling himself with his own silver hand. <ref name=encyc>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of AFL Footballers: every AFL/VFL player since 1897 |last1=Holmesby|first1=Russell|last2=Main|first2=Jim |year=2014 |edition=10th |isbn=978-1-921496-32-5 |publisher=BAS Publishing |location=Seaford, Victoria |page=702}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{AFL Tables | P/Peter_Pettigrew }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettigrew, Peter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{AFL-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About||the fictional character in the Harry Potter series of novels and films|Peter Pettigrew (character)|the Canadian politician|Pierre Pettigrew}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Peter Pettigrew\n| image = \n| fullname = Peter Pettigrew\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|09|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = East Reservoir\n| height = 177 cm\n| weight = 72.5 kg\n| position = \n| statsend = 1972\n| years1 = 1970\u201372\n| club1 = {{AFL Col}}\n| games_goals1 = 19 (5)\n| careerhighlights = \n}}\t\t\n\t\t\n'''Peter Pettigrew''' (born 9 September 1950) is  a former [[Australian rules football]]er who played with [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] (VFL).<ref name=encyc>{{cite book |title=The Encyclopedia of AFL Footballers: every AFL/VFL player since 1897 |last1=Holmesby|first1=Russell|last2=Main|first2=Jim |year=2014 |edition=10th |isbn=978-1-921496-32-5 |publisher=BAS Publishing |location=Seaford, Victoria |page=702}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{AFL Tables | P/Peter_Pettigrew }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettigrew, Peter}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{AFL-bio-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:1a22:5600:e4a9:5acf:89c7:e7d6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Pettigrew"}
